alpha_beta

https://www.ics.uci.edu/~rickl/courses/cs-171/2012-wq-cs171/2012-wq-cs171-lecture-slides/2012wq171-07-Games.pdf













Alpha = Minimum (i.e. Worst MIN can force onto MAX if MAX plays well => highest choice at MAX selection)
Beta = Maximum (i.e. Best MAX can do if MIN plays well => lowest choice at MIN selection)

MAX updates alpha value, MIN updates beta value




MAX updates Alpha "based on kids"

Branches can be ordered so no pruning takes place
Best moves are found first and allow lesser moves to be pruned
USE ANSWER FROM LAST COMPLETED DEPTH
NOT PARTIALLY COMPLETED SEARCH
Seems to violate the partially searched depth rule


https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Transposition_table
Such a table is a hash table of each of the positions analyzed so far up to a certain depth
The usage of transposition tables is essentially memoization applied to the tree search
